title: Democracy Day Sioux Falls
description:
Democracy Day Sioux Falls
Political Rally in Support of Veterans
Food / Cash Donation Drive to support South Dakota DAV
Friday, June 6th, 2026 5:00 pm to 7:00 pm
12th & Kiwanis Sioux Falls SD


Concerned citizens plan to gather again, this time to speak out and stand up for Veterans. A rally and food drive is planned for Friday, June 6th, 2025. Community members are invited to gather for Democracy Day Sioux Falls from 5:00 to 7:00 pm on 12th and Kiwanis in Sioux falls. Rally goers are encouraged to bring signs showing their support, along with a non perishable food donation for Vets in need.
Organized by the same group of anonymous citizens of the April 19th rally and food drive at Van Eps park, an event provided a 3,400 pound food donation and raised over $4000.00 given to Feeding South Dakota. Hopes for a larger turn out at the USS South Dakota Battleship Memorial are high with the event planned to also remember the historic events of June 6th, 1944 and the invasion of Normandy. 
‚ÄúThe memorial is sometimes overlooked for its significance in history. It was called Battleship X to protect its identity in the Pacific theater, because of its success in combat, defending freedom during World War II, ending the fascist regime of the Axis Powers. It‚Äôs appropriate to gather there on the anniversary of D-Day to demand better care and protections for our Service Members today.‚Äù  organizers said.
Non-perishable food items and cash donations will support local South Dakota DAV Arthur H. Muchow Chapter No.1. Those interested in donating but not able to stay for the rally will be able to drive through and drop off donations. A DAV trailer will be at the site for the duration of the event.
The public is called to make an impact in awareness of the concerns of the community. For more information on volunteering or attending an event page is available on Facebook, find it by searching #DemocracyDaySiouxFalls

title: Reject Bullying and Harassment in Sarasota County Schools
description:
We‚Äôre reaching out because Sarasota County students urgently need your support.

Sarasota County Schools has drafted changes to its Student Code of Conduct that would remove key protections for all students, including our LGBTQ youth. This harmful action will send a message that some students are less worthy of safety and respect. Sarasota County Schools has no basis to remove language that affirms the ability for LGBTQ students to ‚Äúattend school in an environment where all students and adults are treated equally‚Äù. 

Despite what the district says, this is not about compliance or any legal requirement. There are no State or Federal laws or any Executive Orders over the last 100 days, requiring school districts to remove any of these student protections. This decision will simply result in more harassment, increased bullying instances, and strips our students of the right to attend a safe school.

Now is the time to speak up. We need you to attend the school board meeting, share a public comment, and show that this community stands up for all students.

We urge Sarasota County Schools to focus on creating safe, fair, and welcoming schools. This is the bare minimum to ensure every student wants to attend school, feels safe, and can focus on their academics. Sarasota County Schools must prioritize student safety and learning, not subject our kids to harassment and discrimination.

title: Fight Censorship at Waupun Public Library
description:
Join local Indivisibles in a pre-library board meeting protest, and sign up to speak against a local man who has been repeatedly requesting LGBTQIA+ material censorship at the Waupun Public Library. 

Background: A man who goes by Mr Gappa, from the Waupun, WI has sent multiple letters and has been speaking at library board meetings vehemently pushing for the removal of any library material with reference to or portrays the LGBTQIA+ community or lifestyle. He has now spoken to the Waupun city council and is smearing the name of one of the board members spouse as he continues to push back against this censorship request. 
There was a large showing for speakers, almost unanimously in opposition to the censorship, at the February board meeting. Since then, he has sent yet another letter to the board calling for his own religion be used as a guide for content, material and displays at the PUBLIC library. 
Let‚Äôs help support the overwhelming consensus among the community that censorship does NOT belong in our public libraries.
Plan to meet at the Waupun Public Library, 123 S Forest St, Waupun, WI at 4pm. Protestors should line the street on both S Forest and E Brown streets. Board meeting begins at 4:30pm. If you wish to speak, you must sign in prior to the meeting start - there is limited seating in the board room (a capacity of about 100 seats). 
Parking is limited and is mostly street parking.

title: Defending Veterans on D-Day

location.venue: Marin Veterans' Memorial Auditorium Parking Lot

description:
June 6, 2025, marks the 81st anniversary of D-Day, the day the Allied forces launched the biggest sea invasion with a singular goal: overthrow the fascists of Nazi Germany. This year, we will honor the many men who fought and died that day, and we will continue their fight ‚Äì this time on America‚Äôs shores and in America‚Äôs streets.  On Friday, June 6, veterans and their allies will join once again for a rally in front of the Marin Veterans Memorial Auditorium.

This rally will take place on the same day as the primary gathering on the National Mall in Washington, D.C., as well as in state capitols, large cities and small towns. Veterans and military family members are being fired by the thousands from federal jobs. Their healthcare is being gutted. Their benefits are under siege. We rally to:

Defend veteran and military family member employment in the federal workforce;

Stop the privatization and weakening of the Department of Veterans Affairs; and

Hold political leaders accountable for policies that harm veterans and their families.

The rally will include firsthand accounts from veterans and their providers on the difficulties they are experiencing in receiving and providing care. 



[Photo by ProBonoPhoto.org/Stephanie Mohan]

description:
Representative Pramila Jayapal has worked with experts in the fields and developed a "Resistance Lab" course. You can join the next one on June 1st virtually [here](https://www.mobilize.us/pramilaforcongress/event/775585/). But for people in the Seattle area, we are planning an in-person session to watch the training together. The course includes group exercises, which would be much easier and fun to do together in person. 

We will be meeting at a Seattle Public Library branch in the University District area. Please note, this event is NOT hosted, sponsored, or endorsed by The Seattle Public Library. Any views that are discussed in this meeting are not a reflection of The Seattle Public Library‚Äôs views.

**This in-person meeting has limited capacity. We kindly ask you to only sign up if you plan to attend the session. If your plan changes, please cancel your registration promptly so that others can sign up and we can prepare accordingly. **

If you have any questions, please feel free to contact us via this [form](https://forms.gle/GCAi5a6m45SvyP1g9).

### What is the Resistance Lab? 
(copied from [Representative Jayapal's page](https://www.pramilaforcongress.com/the-resistance-lab))

The Resistance Lab is a series of trainings that are developed specifically for this moment. We look at how non-violent movements around the world have responded to leaders who seize power in authoritarian ways and the most effective tools and tactics to utilize in these moments.  We offer frameworks to understand this moment at home, and incorporate interactive conversation with others to help create community and build our resistance movement.   

The Resistance Lab was developed with experts who have researched and studied democratic backsliding around the world as well as in the United States and the non-violent movements that have emerged to challenge those authoritarian leaders.  We also draw from many toolkits for effective tactics and frameworks as well as from Pramila‚Äôs own background leading successful organizing movements for economic and social justice for two decades.  

Our goals are to help people understand how democracies fall and the most effective resistance movements that have challenged authoritarians and dictators; to turn anger, fear and frustration into action in the short-term while also preparing for a coordinated resistance movement for the longer term; and to build community across the country that can help grow our movement.  At the end of the day, we want to get people strike-ready and street-ready and make sure we protect our people, our freedoms and our democracy.  

With Trump and his MAGA billionaires doubling down on their attacks on the economic livelihoods of people to thrive and on our democracy, we can‚Äôt afford to sit this moment out. This is about building real power together. And it starts with you. 


### Interviews about The Resistance Lab
Here is [an interview on The Rachel Maddow Show](https://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow/watch/-there-s-no-other-savior-or-option-resistance-to-trump-mobilizes-as-americans-have-seen-enough-235933765750) about it.

Stacey Abrams talked to Representative Jayapal about it [on her podcast](https://youtu.be/0c2QmHu2Flo?si=9f0Jl7kPX4EZni-u&t=337).

title: Fri. 5/30 > Mass Pike Overpass Standout - Southampton Rd (Routes 10/202), Westfield
description:
Wow! What a great location for a standout! About 8 of us tried it out on Friday, May 2, and around 17 of us came out on 5/16. What a blast! LOTS of engagement with motorists!

There's a full-size sidewalk on the west side, and a narrow sidewalk (kind of like the narrow sidewalk at Mountain Park Rd.) on the east side. 

There's lots and lots of traffic passing by. Southampton Road (Routes 10/202) is heavily traveled northbound and southbound, and the Mass Pike eastbound and westbound is below. Lots of honks and thumbs up and waves...and a few folks flying middle fingers. We smile and wave at them all! 

We'll have letterboards prepared for the lower part of the overpass fencing - the photo shows how that will look to folks passing on the Mass Pike. We're interacting with motorists on the Mass Pike, and on Southampton Road. We've discovered that the magic happens when we smile and wave to people!

Come when you can, and leave when you must. You needn't be present for the entire 1 1/2 hours.

### How to Get There

The address "130 Southampton Road, Westfield" will get you just north of the overpass. 

### Parking

We can't park in the Southampton Rd breakdown lane. There are vacant business properties north of the bridge, and it seems that parking would be OK there.

It looks like The Wealth Technology Group has vacated their office at 130 Southampton Rd, but the internet says that other businesses are located there, so please be mindful if you decide to park there.

### Etiquette!

We don't give the finger to people who give the finger to us, or who say unpleasant things. We smile and wave to them, too. 

We may see a counter protester. If so, the best thing to do is just ignore them and spend our time and energy waving to motorists. Let's keep things 100% non-confrontational in words and body language.

### Other Stuff

Please take everything you brought away with you, and leave the site totally clean.

If rain is predicted, we'll cancel. If we cancel, you'll receive an email notification.

### A Few Requests

We've found that roof rake sections make wonderful flagpoles and banner poles. If you have a roof rake (or 10‚Äô-15‚Äô light metal poles or conduit) to contribute, we'll be happy to take it off your hands!

And, if you have an extra 3' x 5' American flag you're not using, we'd love it if you'd pass it on to us!

title: Join us at the We Are The Bridge: Rise For Racial Justice Rally
description:
*East Portland Indivisible proudly supports the Rise for Racial Justice Rally*

Remember George Floyd.

Remember the life that was stolen because of systemic racism and state sanctioned violence.

Remember how we responded, transforming our outrage and grief into an uprising that rocked the entire nation.

Remember that we‚Äôre not done. Our journey has only just begun.

To amplify the movement for Black lives, Brown Hope has convened a grassroots movement called We Are The Bridge: Rise for Racial Justice, a week of action between May 15 ‚Äî May 24 in recognition of George Floyd‚Äôs murder five years ago. This week of action features a series of community gatherings, culminating in a historic rally on May 24th at Revolution Hall and a peaceful march through downtown Portland and the Burnside Bridge.

We march for George Floyd. Breonna Taylor. Quanice Hayes. Kendra James. Eric Garner. Mike Brown. And so many others. We march because this injustice and suffering should never happen again. It should not take the deaths of more Black people for our elected and business leaders to do the right thing.

A grassroots coalition of Portland-based organizations have formed We Are The Bridge: Rise for Racial Justice‚Äî including Brown Hope, 50501 Portland, the Coalition of Black Men, the Oregon Working Families Party, Outside In, SURJ PDX, BIPOC Rise Moor Healing Center, Radical Rest, Veterans For Peace PDX Chapter 72, Restorative Roots Project, and Momentum Alliance. Together, we are calling for immediate action to expand opportunities for our local Black community to thrive‚Äî economically, socially, and spiritually.

**Participants to the Rally - please join us in bringing donations of snacks, water, other basic mutual aid supplies**

Here‚Äôs the complete list of events organized for our week of action:

Nonviolence and De-escalation Training: 6pm on Thursday, May 15 at openHAUS (5020 NE MLK Blvd). Facilitated by the Portland Peace Team, this training teaches how to foster peace during moments of conflict using the CLARA de-escalation method.

Community Grief Circle:12:30pm on Saturday, May 17 at Alberta Park (1905 NE Killingsworth St). Experienced facilitators will lead activities that help attendees release emotional wounds connected to George Floyd‚Äôs murder and racial violence. Concludes with an optional community potluck.

Know Your Rights Training: 6pm on Thursday, May 22nd, Online. Facilitated by the National Lawyers Guild, the workshop covers constitutional rights related to activism and police interactions at first amendment events.

We Are The Bridge Rally and March: noon on Saturday, May 24th at Revolution Hall (1300 SE Stark St). A rally featuring Black and Indigenous leaders, followed by a peaceful march through downtown Portland with a moment of silence on Burnside Bridge.

As we remember George Floyd‚Äôs life and legacy, we must acknowledge that we have the responsibility to act. We Are The Bridge is encouraging supporters to help us build power by donating to local racial justice organizations and promoting the campaign on social media by using the hashtags #BlackLivesMatter and #BeTheBridge.

In 2020, Portland became a beacon of hope for the whole nation and the entire world thanks to 100 days of sustained action in solidarity with Black lives. This year, We Are The Bridge: Rise For Racial Justice is a collective antidote to the disease of moral bankruptcy currently plaguing our country. By participating in this week of action, we can make 2025 a defining year for Portland and our commitment to justice.

We are the heartbeat of this movement. Let‚Äôs work together to inspire a lasting movement of change.

For more information, visit: https://linktr.ee/BrownHope

#BlackLivesMatter #BeTheBridge
